ce:section.ce:para:
Lowering sample temperature to liquid nitrogen temperature at 405 nm excitation practically does not influence the shape of carbon dots emission spectra apart from their intensities. But at the excitation with λexc > 500 nm the low-temperature spectra exhibit clearly expressed doublet structure (see Fig. 2
                      and the insert in the figure). The energy separation between peaks in the doublet is about 1200 cm−1. The similar doublet structure was also observed in low temperature spectra of colloid solution of carbon dots (see Fig. 3
                     ). The variation of the low-temperature spectra in dependence on the excitation wavelength can be explained in the following model. Inhomogeneously broadened spectrum is a superposition of the spectra of various individual emitters. Suppose that the emission spectrum of any emitter in the system consists of two Gaussian-like peaks (as it is shown in the insert of Fig. 3 by solid line) and the number of emitters with a certain emission wavelength is described by the Gaussian distribution with its maximum at 500 nm. The part of emitters excited depends on the excitation wavelength – the shorter is the excitation wavelength the greater is the number of excited emitters which correspond to higher emission frequency. The emission spectrum of the ensemble of the emitters is a sum of the individual spectra of all the emitters that are excited by the given excitation wavelength. The spectra calculated in this model are shown in Fig. 3 by dashed lines. One can see that calculated curves fit well the experimental spectra and the doublet structure manifests itself only at excitation with long enough wavelengths. At shorter wavelength excitation the summation of contributions of many emitters smoothes the doublet structure, this leads to a broad structureless emission band. We suppose that the doublet structure of the emission spectra is due to vibronic transitions in the CDs. The energy separation between the components of the doublet structure (about 1200 cm−1) is close to the energy of CO stretching vibration [16]. It is interesting to note that the similar doublet structure was observed in the emission spectra of single carbon dots, though in the latter case the structure was revealed as a result of deconvolution of the emission spectra only [14]. For single carbon dots the doublet structure was explained by the manifestation of zero-phonon and phonon-assisted electronic transitions in the emission spectra of the dots. The band splitting varies from 70 to 150 meV. The upper limit is close to the splitting value observed in our case (∼150 meV).
